Apr 6 2007 	much to like about this place	My wife and I have stayed in the heart of the strip many times so this time we tried the Silverton to see if we would like the &quot;off strip feel&quot;. We defintely did. The casino and our room were pleaseantly decorated. The room seemed a little larger than typical mid level hotel rooms. It had good quality furnishings and comfortable beds.The staff was very welcoming and friendly. Food in the coffee shop and buffet was certainly good enough (and less expensive than on the strip).  Because this hotel is not next to others, it apparently gets no walk in business so the casino and eating places are not super crowded. The poker room is a good place for low limit cash games and twice a day tournaments. This place has good paying video poker machines. All the casino personal had the attitude that small and off strip is the way to go. The pool area has hot tubs, and a large deck with chairs, tables with umbrellas and cabanas. You should have a car if you want to hit the strip and/or shopping places. There is a car rental in town that has much lower rates than the airport or strip offices. In summary this is a relaxing place to stay away from the heart of the strip which has become very, very crowded.	
Apr 4 2007 	quiet and comfortable	First of all if you're looking for the glitz and glamour of the strip you might want to look somewhere else. Simply put, the property is older but quiet and comfortable. One thing that did stand out was everyone associated with the Silverton was friendly and helpful. I'm sure they have to be to to compete with the more modern establishments. We stayed here during our trip to see the Mariners play the Cubs during spring training. They split one to one by the way.If you plan on going anywhere you have three choices, rent a car (we did) take a taxi (about 10 to 15 dollars to the strip) or take the bus that stops right outside for a minimum charge. Parking for your vehicle is valet or the free parking lot which can amount to a healthy walk as they share with the Bass Pro Shop which is next door.Check in was a breeze and took about 5 minutes. Check out is via the express method if you wish to leave a major credit card on file. Your bill is updated on the television in you room so you know exactly what your bill will be when you leave.Our room was clean and ready upon our arrival, which was two hours early. It was older and one bedside lamp took a special twist to get working but otherwise lots of hot water and the bed was very comfortable, much like the Marriott's beds. One thing that did bother us was it appears the house keeping staff was rather indifferent. They forgot to change the water glasses twice and reline the used ice bucket, maybe alittle picky but you are paying to return to a clean room. Through out our stay we never heard another guest or noise from the hallway. The place was apparently built during the time when hotels actually used soundproofing.We ate at the cafe, buffet and the Mexican restaurant. The cafe had a large American style breakfast and lunch menu and we found the value and taste excellent. We tried the buffet which was a good value also. The buffet offered 5 different cuisines and prime rib, which was done perfectly. Try the shrimp, they were excellent. Desserts were mediocre. The Mexican restaurant was also good, service was friendly but the food to table was slow.As for the Casino, if your a hard core gambler it's the place for you. They still have 5 dollar tables with two deck shoes and the machines are dated. I didn't see anyone winning big on the machines. But there seemed to be a lot of hollering from the craps table. For the most part the patrons are middle aged with some locals mixed in. Unlike downtown sobriety didn't seem to be a problem.A tip for the first time stay. Rent a car and you can drive to the strip and park in about 15 minutes if you know when to go an where to go. Stay off the freeways between 6 and 9 in the morning and anytime from 4 to 8 in the afternoon. They are absolute gridlock. And if you can't get down Las Vegas Blvd. before 11 in the morning don't bother, unless you don't mind traveling two miles in about one hour. Instead drive out the Silverton driveway and go into town on Dean Martin drive. This road skirts the strip on the opposite side of the freeway and goes directly into town. We drove into town and parked in the Fashion Mall parking lot in front of the Macy's entrance. From there it's a one block walk to the strip right in front of Wynn's Resort, don't miss visiting Wynn's. The bus stop is also directly in front of the mall and is one of Vegas' best kept travel secret. Hope this review helped. If I were going to spend anymore than three days in Vegas I would probably stay here again with no problem. If I were to go to Vegas for the glitz and glamour, not worrying about peace and quiet, I'd probably stay on the strip.	
