Oct 25 2006	Off strip locations	We've been to Las Vegas about 20 times and each time we have a &quot;base&quot; hotel for part to fhe stay and always try to find some where new to try. This time it was the Silverton. It is about 5 milese south of the strip. We always have a car, which is cheaper than cabs, so getting around is not a problem. We tried this hotel, because of the Bass Pro Shop that is attached. My husband doesn't gamble all that much, but is a sportsman and I thought he would enjoy the shop. It is absolutely fabulous.To top things off, the hotel was way above our expectations. It was not only clean, but newly remodeled. We won at the casino, which is not a mega place, and the staff is great. Staying off the strip, we have found is a great way to win and have your money go farther. The Silverton has a shuttle that goes to the strip for those who do not have a car. We will return to this hotel. After 2 nights there we moved to our &quot;base&quot; hotel of Sam's Town. A far larger casino than the Silverton, but still the same great staff. The hotel has been remodeled and has a variety of things to do with the bowling alley, movie theatre, and several dining choices and bars. If being on the crowded strip is not important to you, try one of these hotels. You will b pleasantly surprised.	
Oct 12 2006 	Great Beds 	We booked this room through Vegas at a rate of $44.00 for a Thursday night. I chose this hotel based on TripAdvisor reviews. We were looking for just one night's good sleep outside of Vegas for our family, and boy, was the sleep great.! The beds were very comfortable and the room was oversized.The hotel was easy to find from the airport using mapquest directions although at the time (September 2006) there is construction going on in the area, so watch the signs and the traffic. It's a little tricky.The parking lot was a little confusing going just one-way in spots and finding the front desk was a challenge. I know it's a casino and you have to travel that maze to get to anything, but it's still a pain--especially with two little kids in tow. We did not come to gamble and cannot comment on anything like that except to say that I hated dragging them through the smokey casino. But I knew this when I booked the room. I would not stay here on a long term basis for this reason alone, but for one night after a 7 hour flight, the spacious rooms and comfy beds were worth the quick entrance and exit.The hotel is attached to a Bass Pro Shop and the area between the store and the casino has a huge fish tank that periodically features a live &quot;mermaid&quot; which was the highlight of our 4 year old little girl's stay. She got to see &quot;Ariel&quot; who was tastefully clothed in a mermaid suit that had a flesh colored suit underneath--so you weren't really seeing what you thought you were seeing. A plus for us prudes. She swam with stingrays, small sharks and other fish and even came to the glass to interact with our daughter.Our room was ready when we arrived around 1pm local time. It was oversized with two queen beds with heavenly pillow-top matresses and very comfortable pillows. We were on the 4th floor which was supposed to be non-smoking, but there was always a faint odor of smoke, possibly rising up from the casino or other floors. Our room did not smell as if it had been smoked in.The room was clean, spacious and cool in the 90 degree heat. The air conditioner worked great, but was a bit loud. We did not mind and did not need to use our white-noise machine. But if you like quiet, it was loud. The drapes darkened the room well when we went to bed early because we had come from a different time zone.Our room overlooked the pool which was lit up beautifully in the dark, but we did not swim. Did I say that the beds were fabulous? Better than any $40 hotel I've ever stayed at. Come to think of it, I don't think I ever did stay at a $40 hotel before! But book through Vegas.com to get a better price than you can get through their regular website. Rooms at this price are limited so book early if you can.The bathroom was average and included a hairdryer, but the bonus was the Bath &amp; Body Works toiletries. It was a nice touch. No cheap hotel soap here.I would definitely stay here again if I was coming through town, there is a lot of room for the children to move around in, a table to have dinner at (only two chairs) and a Bass Pro Shops next door. I believe they have an RV Park too and several restaurants which we did not visit. Just a short drive away is the very bottom of Las Vegas Blvd. and several places to eat and a grocery store. We also purchased a double CD containing about 16-18 songs that was in the room for $12.99 which seemed reasonable. It was a nice variety of music from Aretha Franklin to Sonny &amp; Cher, Captain &amp; Tenille to Bonnie Tyler. It did not seem overpriced as many hotel items are. Speaking of which, there were $6 bottles of Evian and a mini bar available, but we didn't even open them up.I would not stay here long term simply because of the faint smell of smoke (we are asthmatics) and because the children had to walk through the casino to get anywhere, but it is a VERY comfortable place to stay after a long flight, passing through or for adults only.	
